[2] Pigs, people and climate
Date: Thu 3 Mar 2022
Source: The Sydney Morning Herald [edited]
https://www.smh.com.au/national/three-in-hospital-amid-fears-of-japanese-encephalitis-spreading-from-pigs-to-people-20220302-p5a0wp.html


There are 3 Victorians in hospital with suspected cases of Japanese encephalitis after health authorities discovered a massive outbreak at pig farms across Australia's south-east that had gone undetected for weeks.

Japanese encephalitis is generally harmless but in the fewer than 1% of cases where symptoms do develop, one patient in 3 will die. A vaccine is available, but there is no treatment.

Globally, the mosquito-borne virus, which spreads between waterbirds, pigs and humans, kills about 17 000 people a year, but it has never been seen south of Cape York. Experts say the deadly disease was brought here by the warming climate and is now here to stay.

"We never expected to see it in southern regions of Australia. This has taken a lot of us by surprise," said Associate Professor Cameron Webb, an expert in the virus, based at the University of Sydney.

The unexpected arrival of the disease explains why, when several pig farms reported a mysterious and concerning rise in piglet stillbirths, it took authorities several weeks to even consider testing for Japanese encephalitis.

When they got the results back on Friday [25 Feb 2022], they discovered an enormous outbreak. Biological sampling revealed the virus at 9 piggeries, which stretch more than 1000 kilometres from Goondiwindi in south-east Queensland all the way down to Lockington in Victoria's north.

Piggeries with confirmed infections of Japanese encephalitis [A map of the locations is accessible at the above URL]

Australia's Chief Veterinary Officer, Mark Schipp, said those piggeries housed about 150 000 pigs. There are probably twice that number of feral pigs living nearby, so "we are unlikely to be able to eradicate the virus", Dr Schipp said. Another 5 piggeries are under investigation.

Victorian health authorities issued a warning on Saturday [26 Feb 2022] following the discovery of the virus at the piggeries. At that point, there were no confirmed cases in humans. Since then, 4 human cases have been identified in Victoria, with 3 people now in hospital.

Other types of virus that cause encephalitis in Australia include Murray Valley encephalitis and West Nile virus.

Health authorities are also aware of several encephalitis cases of unknown cause across NSW, Victoria and South Australia over the past month. Japanese encaphalitis is not habitually tested for because, until now, no one thought it was here. The NSW and South Australian health departments said on Wednesday [2 Mar 2022] that they did not have any confirmed cases.

Fewer than 1% of people who are infected develop clinical illness, but in those who do, the virus can be deadly as it moves into the spinal cord and brain. Children face extra risks and are often left with significant brain injuries.

"It's pretty dangerous. You don't want to get it," said Scott Ritchie, an adjunct professor at James Cook University, who has published several papers on the virus.

"It can kill you, or it can induce long-term neurological effects. You might be in a coma, paralysis. It is a nasty disease."

On Wednesday [2 Mar 2022], Victoria's Health Department said it did not have any detail of the condition of the 3 people in hospital.

In a statement issued on Saturday [26 Feb 2022], Chief Health Officer Brett Sutton warned Victorians of the dangers of the virus.

"Most people will have no, or very mild, symptoms, but anyone who develops a sudden onset of fever, headache and vomiting should see their doctor immediately," Professor Sutton said.

"People with these symptoms can deteriorate over just a few short days, including suffering a loss of co-ordination, disorientation, generalised weakness and, in some cases, issues with movement which can last for years."

Japanese encephalitis is spread by infected mosquitoes and waterbirds, which pass the virus between each other. The problem comes when mosquitos carry the virus into pigs, who can generate extremely high viral loads. Mosquitos can then carry the virus from pig to human. It cannot be spread from human to human.

This is how much of the country had record or very much above average rainfall over summer [A map showing rainfall amounts in Australia 1 Dec 2021-28 Feb 2022 at the source URL]

Health authorities are considering rolling out the vaccine to pig workers.

Tim Kingma, the president of the Victorian Farmers Federation's Pig Group told the ABC he wasn't particularly worried about the virus. "It was a bit daunting on the morning to hear about it. Our 1st thoughts go to the people we employ, our communities, our kids," he said. "In terms of worry, there are a lot worse exotic diseases out there. This one has no effect on meat. The issue purely is a mosquito can transfer this from a pig to a human."

Exactly how the virus came to infect pigs across eastern Australia is unclear, and might never be known for certain.

The virus has been genomically linked to fatal cases in the Tiwi Islands in March 2021 and Papua New Guinea. That suggests it was carried to the Australian mainland by migrating waterbirds -- or mosquitoes blown by monsoon rains.

The virus probably landed before La Nina's huge summer rains created a "conveyer belt" for infected waterbirds and mosquitoes to head south, said Professor Webb. Murray Valley encephalitis tends to move in much the same way, he said.

Professor Webb said the climate crisis "certainly plays a role" in the spread of the virus by increasing the likelihood of extreme rainfall.

Ongoing rain and flooding means conditions will be perfect for the virus for several months, but as they recede the risk is likely to fall, though infected mosquito eggs can survive for years, hatching again in the next La Nina season.

Authorities will try to control the virus by cutting mosquito numbers in infected areas, and limiting the movement of pigs. A pig cull is off the table as there are too many feral animals -- and too many waterbirds.

The federal health department is asking people who live in areas of eastern Australia with large numbers of mosquitoes to take steps to avoid being bitten by wearing long clothing and using mosquito repellent.

[Byline: Liam Mannix]

