[ProMED thanks Irene Lai for submitting the official report in item 3 above.

The recognition of the presence of Japanese encephalitis (JE) virus in mainland Australia and the response to it is an excellent example of a comprehensive, one health approach to a new emerging disease situation. Pig farmers in several localities recognized that something was wrong with their animals. Their veterinarians collected appropriate samples from the pigs. Timely laboratory support identified JE virus in those samples. The presence of wild, feral pigs was taken into account in the decision not to cull affected domestic piggeries. Knowing that JE is a zoonotic disease, public health authorities issued an alert to health care providers. Human cases were quickly diagnosed. Vaccination of humans was made available. The environmental conditions favoring proliferation of vector mosquito populations, ample rainfall and flooding, was assessed. The occurrence of JE virus transmission over a wide geographic area raises the question of whether the virus now has become established in mainland Australia in areas where it has not been detected before. Doubtless, intensified, ongoing surveillance for human and pig disease and for presence of the virus in vector mosquitoes will be ongoing in eastern and southern Australia. - Mod.TY

